dspace” or “space of possible minds.” By plotting properties of mind without prioritizing the human, Ball sheds new light on a host of fascinating questions: What moral rights should we afford animals, and can we understand their thoughts? Should we worry that AI is going to take over society? If there are intelligent aliens out there, how could we communicate with them? Should we? Understanding mindspace also reveals ways of making advances in understanding some of the most challenging questions in contemporary science: What is thought? What is consciousness? And what (if anything) is free will? Informed by conversations with leading researchers, Ball’s brilliant survey of current views about the nature and existence of minds is more mind-expanding than we could imagine. In this fascinating book of minds, we come to better know our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aArtificial intelligence. 0aBrain. 0aCognition in animals. 0aCognition. 0aConsciousness. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  amind, brain, consciousness, cognition, understanding, neuroscience, computer science, astrobiology, zoology, plants, aliens, god, humanity, human nature, nonfiction, rights, morality, ethics, animals, carnism, thoughts, artificial intelligence, robots, rise of the machines, free will, agency, philosophy, psychology, extraterrestrial life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226822044423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226822044/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles